\subsection*{4.6.3 Epiglottitis}

Epiglottitis is a medical emergency that may result in death if not treated quickly. It is mainly caused by the bacteria H. influenzae type b but may also be caused by other bacteria or viruses associated with upper respiratory infections. Epiglottitis usually begins as an inflammation and swelling between the base of the tongue and the epiglottis. The swelling may obstruct the airway.

\section*{Diagnosis}
sore throat with difficulty in speaking
- difficulty in breathing
soft stridor
fever
drooling of saliva
difficulty in swallowing or inability to drink.

\section*{Treatment}

Treatment of patients with epiglottitis is directed to relieving the airway obstruction and eradicating the infectious agent.
- Keep the child calm, and provide humidified oxygen, with close monitoring.
- Avoid examining the throat if the signs are typical, to avoid precipitating obstruction.

Call for help and secure the airway as an emergency because of the danger of sudden, unpredictable airway obstruction. Elective intubation is the best treatment if there is severe obstruction but may be very difficult; consider the need for surgical intervention to ensure airway patency.
- Give IV antibiotics when the airway is safe: ceftriaxone at $80 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ once daily for 5 days.

