- Give amoxicillin at $50 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ orally before the operation or, if the child is unable to take oral medications, ampicillin at $50 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ IV within 30 min of surgery.
- For major surgery, give premedication to allay anxiety.

\subsection*{9.1.2 Intraoperative care}

Successful procedures require teamwork and careful planning. The operating room staff should function as a team, including surgeons, anaesthesia staff, nurses, scrub technicians and others. Ensure that essential supplies are readily available before the start of the operation.

\section*{Anaesthesia}

Infants and children experience pain just like adults, but may express it differently.
- Make the procedure as painless as possible.
- For minor procedures in cooperative children, give a local anaesthetic by local infiltration, such as:
- lidocaine at $3 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ ( $0.3 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg}$ of $1 \%$ solution and $0.15 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg}$ of $2 \%$ solution; maximum dose, 200 mg ), not repeated within 2 h
- bupivacaine at $0.5-2.5 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ as a $0.25 \%$ or $0.5 \%$ solution; maximum dose, $1 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg}$ of $0.25 \%$ solution, $0.5 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg}$ of $0.5 \%$ solution ( $2.5 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ )
- For major procedures, give general anaesthesia.

Ketamine is an excellent anaesthetic when muscle relaxation is not required.
- Insert an intravenous cannula. It may be more convenient to delay this until after ketamine has been given IM.
- Induction and maintenance of anaesthesia (short procedures) and analgesia for short painful procedures:
- Give ketamine at $5-8 \mathrm{mg}$ IM or $1-2 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ IV over 60 s for surgical anaesthesia, adjusted according to response. The child should be ready in 2-3 min if given IV or 3-5 min if given IM.
- Give a further dose of ketamine at $1-2 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ IM or $0.5-1 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ IV if the child responds to a painful stimulus.
- Induction and maintenance of anaesthesia (longer procedures) by continuous IV infusion:
- Neonate: Give initially $0.5-2 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ loading dose followed by a continuous IV infusion of $500 \mu \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{kg}$ per h, adjusted according to response; up to $2 \mathrm{mg} /$ kg per h can be used to produce deep anaesthesia.
- Infant or child: Give initially $0.5-2 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ loading dose followed by a continuous IV infusion of $0.5-2.5 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ per h, adjusted according to response.
- At the end of the procedure, turn the child into the lateral position and closely supervise recovery in a quiet place.

